        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer5047363" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9572069149781197561">The Varieties of Scientific Experience is a transcript of Carl Sagan&apos;s presentation of the Gifford Lectures. <br/><br/>While each lecture is self contained, the come together as a whole - each obliquely addressing questions about man&apos;s place in the universe, basic science, the relationship of rational inquiry to religion, and the implications of belief in extraterrestrial life.<br/><br/>Here, Sagan is presented in his typical form. He is at once witty, understandable, profound, and compassionate. <br/><br/>Of particular inte</span>
  <span id="freeText9572069149781197561" style="display:none">The Varieties of Scientific Experience is a transcript of Carl Sagan's presentation of the Gifford Lectures. <br /><br />While each lecture is self contained, the come together as a whole - each obliquely addressing questions about man's place in the universe, basic science, the relationship of rational inquiry to religion, and the implications of belief in extraterrestrial life.<br /><br />Here, Sagan is presented in his typical form. He is at once witty, understandable, profound, and compassionate. <br /><br />Of particular interest is the transcript of the various Q&amp;A sessions which accompanied the lectures. Sagan displays great charm and humanity in his handling of those who attempt to attack his ideas. It's truly incredible to observe the confident humility of one of science's greatest minds.</span>
